<dl id="n26092r"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n26" href="#n26092r">N26 (VI.B.18)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n26all.htm#n26092r"> 92(r)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Amice ut offeras</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">But cases hardly less serious undoubtedly occurred at an early date. The gross venality of the papal curia, even in the early thirteenth century, is not a very happy omen for the behaviour of private patrons; smaller folk than the Pope could summon a wretched abbot &ldquo;<mark>Amice, ut offeras</mark>&rdquo;; nor was it only abbots who thus bought themselves into favour. <small> Eileen Edna Power, <a name="MLEN" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#MLEN"><cite title="source">Medieval English Nunneries</cite></a> (1922) 56</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Written sideways in left margin.</mm> </dd></dl>
